Mario Austin had 24 points and 10 rebounds
as No. 16 Mississippi State extended its winning streak to seven
games with a 78-54 victory over Georgia State on Wednesday night.
article.headline: Mississippi State wins seventh straight game
article.linkText: Austin powers No. 17 Bulldogs over Georgia State
article.story:
JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- Just when it looked like Georgia State was
about to make a game of it against Mississippi State, the Bulldogs
tightened up the defense and turned it into rout.

	   Mario Austin had 24 points and 10 rebounds as  (No. 17 ESPN/USA Today, No. 16 AP) Mississippi
State extended its winning streak to seven games with a 78-54
victory Wednesday night.

	   Timmy Bowers scored 11 points and Derrick Zimmerman had 10
assists for the Bulldogs (7-1), who held Georgia State (3-4)
scoreless for more than seven minutes in the second half after the
Panthers pulled within eight points.

	   "Defensively, we weren't very sharp in the first half as
evidence by their 37 points,'' Mississippi State coach Rick
Stansbury said. "I thought in the second half things picked up for
us defensively.''

	   The Panthers scored just 17 points in the second half, shooting
28 percent.

	   Austin was playing in his second game after sitting out the
first six while the NCAA sorted through questions about his
eligibility. The 6-foot-9 junior followed up his 28-point
performance against Xavier last Saturday with another stellar game,
despite the Panthers' best efforts to crowd the paint.

	   Austin had 14 points in the first half against Georgia State's
zone. The Panthers went man-to-man to start the second half, but
that didn't work either.

	   Austin scored the Bulldogs' first six points of the second half,
the last two on a feathery finger roll that put Mississippi State
up 49-39.

	   Austin was 10-for-16 from the field, but even he was thinking
defense first.

	   "I just want to go in and just make hustle plays. I know the
offense will come if I play great defense,'' he said.

	   The Bulldogs also dominated the glass, outrebounding Georgia
State 52-21. The Bulldogs had more offensive rebounds (25) than the
Panthers had total boards.

	   "They're a lot better than us,'' Georgia State coach Lefty
Driesell said bluntly. "If we played them 10 times they would beat
us. We did the best we could.''

	   Reserve forward Cedric Patton led the Panthers with 21 points,
including 17 in 11 minutes in the first half. Lamont McIntosh had
12 for Georgia State, which has lost three straight and next plays
at No. 7 Oklahoma.

	   The Bulldogs also have Oklahoma next on their schedule. They
play the Sooners on Dec. 28 in New Orleans, but certainly could not
be accused of looking past Georgia State.

	   "We're looking forward to that game,'' Zimmerman said. "The
guy from ESPN said this was probably going to be a slip-up game for
us because they thought we were going to be looking ahead to
Oklahoma. But now we got Oklahoma as our next game and it's going
to be a challenge for us.''

	   The Bulldogs traveled 125 miles from their Starkville campus to
play in Jackson, the state's capital and largest city, for the
first time in four years.

	   The Bulldogs gave the sellout crowd of 6,592 in the Mississippi
Coliseum a good show, taking the lead early and controlling the
game with their athletic perimeter players complementing Austin's
inside game.

	   McIntosh hit consecutive 3-pointers for Georgia State to cut the
lead to 56-48 with 10 minutes left.

	   Mississippi State answered by scoring the next 15 points, six by
Winsome Frazier, to go up 71-48 with 3 minutes left.

	   Walk-on Seth Cannon capped the Bulldogs' seventh straight
double-digit win by banking home a shot from 10 feet beyond the
midcourt line at the buzzer.

	   Patton kept Georgia State close by going 5-for-6 from the field,
including three 3-pointers, in the first half. The rest of the
Panthers were 9-for-25 as Mississippi State took a 43-37 halftime
lead.
